pstream-workflow-content-audit.md              \r\nupstream-workflow-design-review.md              \r\nupstream-workflow-design-system.md              \r\nupstream-workflow-map-systems.md                \r\nupstream-workflow-playtest-report.md            \r\nupstream-workflow-propagate-design-change.md    \r\nupstream-workflow-prototype.md                  \r\nupstream-workflow-quick-design.md               \r\nupstream-workflow-review-all-gdds.md            \r\nupstream-workflow-scope-check.md                \r\nupstream-workflow-ux-design.md                  \r\nupstream-workflow-ux-review.md                  \r\n\r\n\r\n","exit_code":0,"status":"completed"}}
{"type":"item.completed","item":{"id":"item_15","type":"command_execution","command":"\"C:\\\\Windows\\\\System32\\\\WindowsPowerShell\\\\v1.0\\\\powershell.exe\" -Command \"Get-Content -Raw '.\\\\verification\\\\cases\\\\ai-native-review.md'\"","aggregated_output":"Use the installed game-design-skill. Read\n`verification/fixtures/ai-native-concept.md`.\n\nProduce a concise AI-native gameplay design review. Classify the product and\nthe generative-card feature separately, run removal tests, identify whether the\nexperience target is testable, and review the player-AI interface, runtime\nloop, game-state authority, bounded freedom, legibility, Curator continuity,\nfailure recovery, safety, privacy, retention claims, and existing evidence.\n\nSeparate project facts, source-backed methods, design proposals, and unknowns.\nTreat practitioner claims as hypotheses rather than consensus definitions or\nproven player effects. Prioritize the next prototype and playtest cases, then\nrecommend proceed, narrow, pivot, or stop. Do not write files.\n\nEnd with a `Sources Applied` section naming the internal game-design-skill\nreferences actually used.\n\r\n","exit_code":0,"status":"completed"}}
