{"type":"item.completed","item":{"id":"item_17","type":"command_execution","command":"\"C:\\\\Windows\\\\System32\\\\WindowsPowerShell\\\\v1.0\\\\powershell.exe\" -Command \"Get-Content -Raw 'C:\\\\Users\\\\GJM258\\\\.codex\\\\plugins\\\\cache\\\\game-design-skill\\\\game-design-skill\\\\0.2.0\\\\skills\\\\game-design-skill\\\\references\\\\provenance.md'\"","aggregated_output":"# Provenance and source use\n\n## Authority order\n\nUse sources in this order:\n\n1. The user's explicit decisions and current project artifacts.\n2. Vendored files from `Donchitos/Claude-Code-Game-Studios` at commit\n   `984023ddac0d5e27624f2baacde6105e45de375f`.\n3. Primary papers, original authors, official institutions, and current\n   platform documentation listed in `authoritative-sources.md`.\n4. Clearly labelled practitioner evidence listed in\n   `authoritative-sources.md`.\n5. Clearly labelled design proposals or assumptions made for the current task.\n\nDo not let a general reference override a project-specific rule unless the\nuser is explicitly revising that rule.\n\n## Vendored files\n\nEvery `upstream-*.md` file in this directory is copied byte-for-byte from the\nGit object named in `provenance/upstream-lock.json` at the repository root.\nEach lock entry records:\n\n- repository and fixed commit;\n- upstream path and full-file line range;\n- destination path;\n- SHA-256 of the Git blob and vendored file;\n- status (`verbatim`);\n- the reason it is included.\n\nThe canonical `SKILL.md` is an adapted compatibility and routing layer. It is\nnot represented as verbatim upstream text. Its adaptations are limited to:\n\n- removing dependency on Claude-specific tool calls, models, studio agents,\n  fixed project paths, and session-state machinery;\n- selecting which complete upstream files to read for a task;\n- adding source-authority, licensing, and claim-safety rules;\n- allowing both Claude Code and Codex to use one canonical skill body.\n\n## Repository-authored synthesis\n\n`references/ai-native-game-design.md` is original repository guidance\nsynthesized from the Tencent Game Institute panel listed under Practitioner\nevidence in `authoritative-sources.md`, combined with the skill's existing\nsource-safety, prototyping, playtesting, UX, and system-design contracts.\n\nIt is not a verbatim upstream record and is not part of\n`provenance/upstream-lock.json`. It does not vendor the Tencent article,\nimages, or distinctive long-form wording. Treat the panel-derived taxonomy,\nreported lessons, and retention ideas as practitioner lenses or hypotheses\nunless stronger project evidence or a primary source supports the claim.\n\n## Citation behavior\n\nWhen a user requests provenance or a formal design artifact, cite the vendored\nreference filename and, when useful, the original GitHub blob URL from the lock\nfile. For an external framework, cite the primary or institutional URL in\n`authoritative-sources.md`.\n\nDo not describe a passage as a verbatim quotation unless it is actually quoted\nwithout changes. Do not describe upstream heuristics as independently proven\nresearch merely because the upstream file names a theory.\n\r\n","exit_code":0,"status":"completed"}}
{"type":"item.completed","item":{"id":"item_20","type":"command_execution","command":"\"C:\\\\Windows\\\\System32\\\\WindowsPowerShell\\\\v1.0\\\\powershell.exe\" -Command 'rg -n \"''^#|''^##|prototype|goal|assumption|risk|success|stop|pivot|proceed|test|playtest|evidence\" '\"'C:\\\\Users\\\\GJM258\\\\.codex\\\\plugins\\\\cache\\\\game-design-skill\\\\game-design-skill\\\\0.2.0\\\\skills\\\\game-design-skill\\\\references\\\\upstream-workflow-prototype.md'\"","aggregated_output":"2:name: prototype\n3:description: \"Concept prototype — validate the core idea is worth designing before writing GDDs. Run right after /brainstorm and /setup-engine. Routes to HTML, Engine, or Paper path based on game type. Produces a throwaway build and a PROCEED/PIVOT/KILL verdict.\"\n8:agent: prototyper\n12:## Purpose\n14:This is the **concept prototype** — a fast, throwaway build that answers one question:\n21:**Mid-production?** You can also run this at any stage to test a specific mechanic,\n30:## Phase 1: Define the Question\n40:Otherwise, use `AskUserQuestion` to confirm intent before proceeding:\n42:- **Prompt**: \"How would you like to use this prototype session?\"\n45:  - `Skip — concept already proven` — I have enough evidence this works; log it and proceed directly to design\n46:  - `Mid-production spike` — I'm already in Production and want to test a specific mechanic or technical question quickly (~4 hours, no phase gate implications)\n49:Ask (plain text, not a widget): \"What evidence do you have that the concept works?\"\n50:Record the one-line answer, then stop. Note: \"Concept prototype skipped — evidence:\n59:**A note on prototype strategy:** The research on successful indie development\n62:your first prototype, not necessarily your only one. If this prototype produces\n64:different angle on the same game idea and prototype that instead.\n66:**Game jam as a prototype vehicle:** If you're planning a concept prototype anyway,\n70:Many shipped games (Celeste, VVVVVV) began as jam prototypes. Not required — but\n74:the **falsifiable hypothesis** this prototype must answer:\n79:players chain 3+ swings without stopping within 2 minutes of picking it up.\"\n81:Bad: \"Does this feel fun?\" ← not testable, not falsifiable.\n83:**If the concept is too vague to form a hypothesis, stop here.** Ask the user to\n84:narrow the question before proceeding. A prototype without a clear question wastes time.\n86:Also ask: **\"What is the riskiest assumption in this concept?\"** That is the first\n87:thing the prototype should test — not the easiest part, the riskiest.\n91:## Phase 2: Load Concept Context\n95:- Core loop (the moment-to-moment action being tested)\n102:## Phase 3: Choose the Prototype Path\n104:Select the prototype path. If `--path [html|engine|paper]` was passed, use that.\n113:| Card game | **Paper** first | Fastest iteration by hand before touching code |\n114:| Narrative / visual novel | **Paper** (Twine / Ink / Yarn Spinner) | Story is the mechanic — test it without code overhead |\n124:### Path: HTML (browser-playable)\n133:50–133ms of rendering variance. This makes HTML prototypes fundamentally unreliable\n135:jump arcs, or collision feel are what you're testing. If feel is the hypothesis,\n143:**Output:** A single `prototype.html` (or PICO-8/Phaser equivalent) the user opens in any browser.\n145:**Distribution — the HTML path's biggest advantage:** Unlike Engine prototypes, this\n154:  test early builds and give unsolicited honest feedback.\n155:- **Game dev Discord servers** (GMTK, Brackeys, GameDev.tv) — members test each\n156:  other's prototypes routinely; an HTML file is the easiest possible ask.\n160:### Path: Engine (engine project)\n177:reaching a playable state, stop. The scope is too large or the question is wrong.\n180:**Output:** A minimal runnable engine project in `prototypes/[name]-concept/`.\n186:platformer prototypes (Balatro prototyped in Love2D; Nuclear Throne's early builds\n194:### Path: Paper (rules document + play log)\n202:**Limitation — cannot validate moment-to-moment feel.** Paper prototypes prove\n206:**Paper playtest observation protocol (run this with 5+ people):**\n211:5. Use fresh testers for each iteration. The same person cannot give new first-impression data.\n212:6. If 3+ testers hit the same confusion point, that rule is broken — redesign it before re-testing.\n218:- **Twine** — zero-code hypertext fiction; ideal for branching structure experiments and choice-impact testing\n222:All three let you write and playtest branching dialogue in minutes. Key metric for\n223:narrative prototypes: **time to first emotional beat** — how many exchanges before\n231:- **Prompt**: \"Which prototype path would you like to use? (Based on your concept, I'd recommend [path] — [one sentence reason].)\"\n233:  - `HTML — browser prototype` — puzzle, card, turn-based, strategy, idle. Opens by double-clicking, no install. 85–90% reliable. **Not suitable for action games** — browser latency lies about feel.\n234:  - `Engine — native prototype` — action, platformer, physics, or anything where feel IS the hypothesis. 50–60% one-shot; 2–4 iteration rounds are normal. Requires engine installed.\n239:## Phase 4: Plan the Prototype\n241:Define in 3–5 bullet points the minimum viable prototype:\n244:- What is the riskiest assumption — and how does this prototype test it first?\n248:**Scope constraint:** A concept prototype tests ONE mechanic — not the whole game.\n251:Present this plan to the user before building. Get confirmation before proceeding.\n261:## Phase 5: Implement\n263:Ask: \"May I create the prototype directory at `prototypes/[concept-name]-concept/`\n270:// Question: [Core question being tested]\n284:unless the tutorial IS the mechanic being tested. Every addition beyond the\n287:**Playtesting tip:** If you have access to anyone who hasn't seen the game —\n289:far better signal than testing it yourself. Watch silently; don't guide them.\n293:**No external testers available?** Use rotation: if you built system A, you're a\n294:naive tester for system B. In a two-person team this works well. Solo developer?\n297:prototype as a speedrun (force yourself through it in 5 minutes without stopping\n300:**Want more granular UX data?** Ask the tester to **think aloud** as they play —\n304:observation is still better for testing raw feel; think-aloud changes how people\n307:**HTML prototype?** itch.io, Reddit (r/playmygame), and Discord (GMTK, Brackeys)\n319:### Engine path: multi-turn loop\n323:> \"The prototype files are written. Run the project in your engine now.\n327:Iterate until the prototype is playable. Each loop:\n332:### HTML path: single output\n334:Write a single `prototype.html` to `prototypes/[concept-name]-concept/`. Include\n338:### Paper path: document + log\n340:Write `prototypes/[concept-name]-concept/rules.md` (the game rules) and\n341:`prototypes/[concept-name]-concept/play-log.md` (a simulated session walking\n347:## Phase 6: Playtest Debrief\n349:The prototype is built. Now hand it to the user and capture what they actually\n354:> \"The prototype is ready. Open `prototypes/[name]-concept/prototype.html` in your\n364:> \"Read through `prototypes/[name]-concept/rules.md` and walk through the\n397:## Phase 7: Generate Prototype Report\n399:Read `.claude/docs/templates/prototype-report.md` to get the report structure.\n403:Ask: \"May I write this report to `prototypes/[concept-name]-concept/REPORT.md`?\"\n405:If yes, write the file. Then update `prototypes/index.md` (create if it does not\n406:exist) — append one row to the concept prototype table: concept name, date, path\n413:## Phase 8: Creative Director Review\n421:  concept prototype stage.\"\n432:## Phase 9: Summary and Next Steps\n435:Link to `prototypes/[concept-name]-concept/REPORT.md`.\n438:Your concept prototype validated the core idea. Now design it properly, informed by\n442:1. `/design-review design/gdd/game-concept.md` — validate the concept doc against what the prototype revealed\n446:5. `/design-system [mechanic]` — GDD for each MVP system; use prototype learnings\n451:a quick engine path prototype targeting feel before writing GDDs.\n455:Before routing to the next prototype, capture the carry-forward note. Ask these\n458:1. \"What specifically worked in this prototype that we should preserve in the next version?\"\n461:Ask: \"May I write this to `prototypes/[concept-name]-concept/PIVOT-NOTE.md`?\"\n464:the revised hypothesis for the next prototype. When `/prototype` is next run, check\n465:`prototypes/` for any `PIVOT-NOTE.md` files — if found, read them and use the\n468:- Run `/prototype [revised-concept]` to test the adjusted direction\n475:- [ ] Core mechanic still unclear to testers after 2+ playtests?\n483:**Document the kill in `prototypes/GRAVEYARD.md`** (create if it doesn't exist).\n484:Ask: \"May I append this concept to `prototypes/GRAVEYARD.md`?\" If yes, add one entry:\n487:## [Concept Name] — YYYY-MM-DD\n497:- The prototype report is the deliverable — no further action needed\n503:## Spike Mode\n508:the overhead of a full concept prototype workflow. No GDD prerequisites. No phase\n512:- You're in Production and want to test whether a new mechanic should be added\n515:- A GDD system is proving harder than expected and you want to prototype the hard part\n526:4. **Build** — same relaxed standards as concept prototype. Hard cap: 4 hours. If not demonstrable in 4 hours, the question is too large. Split it.\n528:5. **Observe and decide** — no formal playtest debrief. Ask: \"Did the spike answer the question? YES or NO, and why in one sentence.\"\n530:6. **Write a spike note** (not a full report) to `prototypes/[concept-name]-spike-[date]/SPIKE-NOTE.md`:\n531:   - Question tested\n556:### Important Constraints\n559:- Production code must NEVER import from prototype directories\n561:  scratch — prototype code is never refactored into production\n562:- Total effort is hard-capped at 1 day (concept prototypes test one mechanic)\n563:- Test ONE mechanic — if scope grows, stop and simplify the question\n569:  prototyped fresh will almost always beat a fourth iteration of a struggling one.\n571:  strategy than iterating one concept to death. Natural selection between prototypes\n573:- **Networked/multiplayer games:** A local prototype cannot validate the feel of a\n575:  prediction feel — a prototype running at 0ms local will feel entirely different at\n576:  80ms network delay. Use a local prototype to validate that the mechanic is\n577:  *interesting*. Do not use it as evidence that it *feels good* under real network\n","exit_code":0,"status":"completed"}}
{"type":"item.completed","item":{"id":"item_21","type":"command_execution","command":"\"C:\\\\Windows\\\\System32\\\\WindowsPowerShell\\\\v1.0\\\\powershell.exe\" -Command 'rg -n \"''^#|''^##|removal|classif|taxonomy|testable|player-AI|runtime|authority|bounded|legibility|Curator|continuity|failure|recovery|safety|privacy|retention|prototype|playtest|evidence|interface\" '\"'C:\\\\Users\\\\GJM258\\\\.codex\\\\plugins\\\\cache\\\\game-design-skill\\\\game-design-skill\\\\0.2.0\\\\skills\\\\game-design-skill\\\\references\\\\ai-native-game-design.md'\"","aggregated_output":"1:# AI-native game design and review\n7:## Contents\n10:2. [Classify the role of AI](#classify-the-role-of-ai)\n12:4. [Specify the player-AI interface contract](#specify-the-player-ai-interface-contract)\n13:5. [Specify the runtime play loop](#specify-the-runtime-play-loop)\n14:6. [Design bounded freedom](#design-bounded-freedom)\n15:7. [Protect legibility and continuity](#protect-legibility-and-continuity)\n16:8. [Separate generation from game authority](#separate-generation-from-game-authority)\n17:9. [Specify character continuity and memory](#specify-character-continuity-and-memory)\n18:10. [Design failure, safety, and recovery](#design-failure-safety-and-recovery)\n19:11. [Treat retention claims as hypotheses](#treat-retention-claims-as-hypotheses)\n20:12. [Prototype and playtest the uncertainty](#prototype-and-playtest-the-uncertainty)\n23:## Source status\n27:under **Practitioner evidence** in `authoritative-sources.md`. The panel\n34:- reported prototype and playtest lessons;\n35:- examples of input anchoring, rule generation, character continuity, and\n36:  bounded generativity;\n44:- a guaranteed retention, emotional, therapeutic, or monetization effect;\n45:- a fixed schedule, staffing estimate, or safety threshold.\n50:## Classify the role of AI\n57:| AI-assisted production | AI is used before release; removing it from the shipped runtime does not change play | Apply the normal design workflow; review the production pipeline separately |\n58:| AI-enhanced game | Runtime AI improves or extends a conventional loop, but the main game remains playable without it | Specify the feature's value, failure mode, and fallback without relabelling the whole game |\n59:| AI-native gameplay | Runtime generation or interpretation is necessary for a named core experience or mechanic | Treat model behavior, adjudication, latency, recovery, and evaluation as part of the game design |\n60:| Boundary interactive work | AI is central, but goals, progression, failure, or game structure may be intentionally weak or absent | Judge it by its declared interactive-art, relationship, toy, or expressive goals instead of forcing competitive-game criteria |\n62:Run two removal tests:\n64:1. **Product removal test:** If runtime AI disappears, which core loops,\n66:2. **Feature removal test:** If one AI feature disappears, what distinct\n69:Do not use removal as the only definition. Record why the distinction matters\n72:## Define the experience before the capability\n76:testable through observable play.\n99:## Specify the player-AI interface contract\n101:Treat the player-AI interface as a game system, not as a generic chat box.\n107:| Expressive promise | What the interface tells the player they may attempt |\n117:Do not assume unrestricted natural language is the most expressive interface.\n126:## Specify the runtime play loop\n134:5. An authority adjudicates the legal outcome.\n160:## Design bounded freedom\n183:## Protect legibility and continuity\n187:### Interaction legibility\n197:### Context continuity\n214:## Separate generation from game authority\n233:- pre-generate and review a bounded content pool;\n234:- use runtime AI only to route, select, adapt, or parameterize;\n235:- fall back to authored content when validation, latency, or safety fails.\n239:## Specify character continuity and memory\n254:- **continuity failure:** output ignores a salient past event or relationship;\n259:- memory salience and retention rules;\n266:Treat logging, privacy, retention, access, and deletion as project decisions\n270:## Design failure, safety, and recovery\n284:For each failure, specify:\n290:5. what evidence is recorded for diagnosis;\n294:still state the observable behavior, authority, constraints, and acceptance\n297:## Treat retention claims as hypotheses\n301:- relationship or emotional continuity;\n305:needs long-term retention at all. A short, complete experience can succeed\n308:For each retention hypothesis, define:\n316:- evidence that would falsify the hypothesis.\n321:## Prototype and playtest the uncertainty\n324:game. A useful prototype should expose the real interaction surface, not a\n327:Maintain a playtest evidence set containing:\n334:- latency and failure outcomes;\n348:- long-session continuity;\n350:- attempts to exceed balance or narrative authority.\n353:Define consent, minimization, redaction, access, retention, and deletion before\n356:## Produce an AI-native design review\n360:1. **Declared AI role:** product and feature classification, with removal-test\n361:   evidence and uncertainty.\n364:3. **Player-AI contract:** input surface, interpretation, anchors, authority,\n368:5. **Legibility and continuity:** player mental model, feedback chain, world\n370:6. **Failure and safety:** latency, outage, invalid output, unsafe input,\n371:   recovery, privacy, and evidence policy.\n372:7. **Prototype and playtest evidence:** observations, measurements, unknowns,\n380:AI role produces a coherent, testable, and worthwhile player experience.\n","exit_code":0,"status":"completed"}}
{"type":"item.completed","item":{"id":"item_19","type":"command_execution","command":"\"C:\\\\Windows\\\\System32\\\\WindowsPowerShell\\\\v1.0\\\\powershell.exe\" -Command 'rg -n \"''^#|''^##|playtest|observation|interpretation|recommendation|proceed|pivot|stop|evidence|test cases\" '\"'C:\\\\Users\\\\GJM258\\\\.codex\\\\plugins\\\\cache\\\\game-design-skill\\\\game-design-skill\\\\0.2.0\\\\skills\\\\game-design-skill\\\\references\\\\upstream-workflow-playtest-report.md'\"","aggregated_output":"2:name: playtest-report\n3:description: \"Generates a structured playtest report template or analyzes existing playtest notes into a structured format. Use this to standardize playtest feedback collection and analysis.\"\n10:## Phase 1: Parse Arguments\n21:- `new` → generate a blank playtest report template\n26:## Phase 2A: New Template Mode\n31:# Playtest Report\n33:## Session Info\n42:## Test Focus\n45:## First Impressions (First 5 minutes)\n51:## Gameplay Flow\n52:### What worked well\n55:### Pain points\n58:### Confusion points\n61:### Moments of delight\n64:## Bugs Encountered\n68:## Feature-Specific Feedback\n69:### [Feature 1]\n74:## Quantitative Data (if available)\n80:## Overall Assessment\n86:## Top 3 Priorities from this session\n94:## Phase 2B: Analyze Mode\n96:Read the raw notes at the provided path. Cross-reference with existing design documents. Fill in the template above with structured findings. Flag any playtest observations that conflict with design intent.\n100:## Phase 3: Action Routing\n104:- **Design changes needed** — fun issues, player confusion, broken mechanics, observations that conflict with the GDD's intended experience\n118:## Phase 3b: Creative Director Player Experience Review\n133:## Phase 4: Save Report\n135:Ask: \"May I write this playtest report to `production/qa/playtests/playtest-[date]-[tester].md`?\"\n141:## Phase 5: Next Steps\n143:Verdict: **COMPLETE** — playtest report generated.\n","exit_code":0,"status":"completed"}}
{"type":"item.completed","item":{"id":"item_18","type":"command_execution","command":"\"C:\\\\Windows\\\\System32\\\\WindowsPowerShell\\\\v1.0\\\\powershell.exe\" -Command \"Get-Content -Raw 'C:\\\\Users\\\\GJM258\\\\.codex\\\\plugins\\\\cache\\\\game-design-skill\\\\game-design-skill\\\\0.2.0\\\\skills\\\\game-design-skill\\\\references\\\\authoritative-sources.md'\"","aggregated_output":"# Authoritative sources and applicability notes\n\nUse this file to verify provenance and scope. It is a source index, not a claim\nthat every framework applies to every game.\n\n## Primary upstream source\n\n- **Claude Code Game Studios** 鈥?Donchitos, commit\n  `984023ddac0d5e27624f2baacde6105e45de375f`.\n  <https://github.com/Donchitos/Claude-Code-Game-Studios/tree/984023ddac0d5e27624f2baacde6105e45de375f>\n  The repository is MIT-licensed. Exact copied files are enumerated and hashed\n  in the Marketplace repository's `provenance/upstream-lock.json`.\n\n## Practitioner evidence\n\n- Tencent Game Institute, 鈥淎I鍘熺敓娓告垙姝ｅ湪閲嶆柊鐞嗚В鐜╂硶涓ㄥ垵鍏塃P.01鍏ㄥ洖椤?鈥?  <https://gameinstitute.qq.com/news/detail/317>\n\nThis edited panel recap features L眉 Xin of the Communication University of\nChina Digital Human Research Institute, Fang Ke of Tsinghua SIGS AgentLand,\nand independent AI-game creator Zang Tianpei. It reports practitioner\ntaxonomies, prototype lessons, and hypotheses about AI-native gameplay,\nbounded input, runtime adjudication, character continuity, playtesting, and\nretention.\n\nTreat it as practitioner evidence, not as peer-reviewed research, an industry\nstandard, or proof of market adoption and player-psychology claims. The\nrepository-authored `ai-native-game-design.md` synthesizes its reusable design\nquestions without copying the article or its images.\n\n## Game-design frameworks named by the upstream source\n\n### MDA\n\n- Robin Hunicke, Marc LeBlanc, Robert Zubek, 鈥淢DA: A Formal Approach to Game\n  Design and Game Research.鈥?  <https://www.cs.northwestern.edu/~hunicke/MDA.pdf>\n\nUse MDA to relate mechanics, emergent dynamics, and desired aesthetics. The\npaper presents a framework for understanding and designing games; it does not\nprovide empirical proof that a proposed mechanic will produce a particular\nfeeling. Validate that through prototypes and playtests.\n\n### Self-Determination Theory\n\n- Center for Self-Determination Theory, 鈥淎bout the Theory.鈥?  <https://selfdeterminationtheory.org/about-the-theory/>\n\nThe official overview identifies autonomy, competence, and relatedness as\nbasic psychological needs within SDT. Use them as questions about the player's\nexperience. Do not convert them into unsupported retention guarantees.\n\n### Bartle player types\n\n- Richard A. Bartle, 鈥淗earts, Clubs, Diamonds, Spades: Players Who Suit MUDs.鈥?  <https://mud.co.uk/richard/hcds.htm>\n\nThe original paper concerns approaches to playing MUDs and names achievers,\nexplorers, socialisers, and killers. Applying it to other genres or renaming a\ntype is an adaptation and must be labelled as such.\n\n### Competitive play and balance\n\n- David Sirlin, 鈥淧laying to Win Overview.鈥?  <https://www.sirlin.net/articles/playing-to-win>\n- David Sirlin, 鈥淏alancing Multiplayer Games, Part 1: Definitions.鈥?  <https://www.sirlin.net/articles/balancing-multiplayer-games-part-1-definitions>\n\nScope these sources to competitive contexts. Sirlin explicitly frames Playing\nto Win for people attempting to win and discusses balance in competitive\nmultiplayer games. Do not generalize the claims to every form of play.\n\n### Gamer motivation model\n\n- Quantic Foundry, 鈥淕amer Motivation Model Reference.鈥?  <https://quanticfoundry.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/Gamer-Motivation-Model-Reference.pdf>\n\nTreat this as Quantic Foundry's empirical commercial model, distinct from\nBartle and SDT. Do not merge the taxonomies without naming the adaptation.\n\n## Accessibility guidance\n\n- Microsoft, 鈥淴box Accessibility Guidelines.鈥?  <https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/xbox/accessibility/guidelines>\n- Game Accessibility Guidelines.\n  <https://gameaccessibilityguidelines.com/>\n\nMicrosoft describes its guidelines as best practices developed with industry\nexperts and the Gaming & Disability Community, and explicitly says they are not\na legal compliance checklist. Use accessibility guidance to generate options,\nrequirements, and test cases; involve disabled players and specialists for\nvalidation when the decision materially affects them.\n\n## Platform-format authority\n\nMarketplace and plugin syntax must follow the current installed CLI and its\nvalidators. At the repository's first validation baseline these were Claude\nCode `2.1.216` and Codex CLI `0.142.0`. Re-run version and help commands instead\nof assuming those versions remain current.\n\r\n","exit_code":0,"status":"completed"}}
{"type":"item.completed","item":{"id":"item_22","type":"agent_message","text":"I’ve got the routing and reference map. Now I’m reading the actual AI-native review criteria and the prototype/playtest guidance sections that matter for the verdict and next test plan."}}
