{"type":"item.completed","item":{"id":"item_26","type":"command_execution","command":"\"C:\\\\Windows\\\\System32\\\\WindowsPowerShell\\\\v1.0\\\\powershell.exe\" -Command '$p='\"'C:\\\\Users\\\\GJM258\\\\.codex\\\\plugins\\\\cache\\\\game-design-skill\\\\game-design-skill\\\\0.2.0\\\\skills\\\\game-design-skill\\\\references\\\\upstream-workflow-playtest-report.md'; \"'$c=Get-Content $p; $c[30..93] -join \"`n\"; \"`n---`n\"; $c[94..118] -join \"`n\"'","aggregated_output":"# Playtest Report\n\n## Session Info\n- **Date**: [Date]\n- **Build**: [Version/Commit]\n- **Duration**: [Time played]\n- **Tester**: [Name/ID]\n- **Platform**: [PC/Console/Mobile]\n- **Input Method**: [KB+M / Gamepad / Touch]\n- **Session Type**: [First time / Returning / Targeted test]\n\n## Test Focus\n[What specific features or flows were being tested]\n\n## First Impressions (First 5 minutes)\n- **Understood the goal?** [Yes/No/Partially]\n- **Understood the controls?** [Yes/No/Partially]\n- **Emotional response**: [Engaged/Confused/Bored/Frustrated/Excited]\n- **Notes**: [Observations]\n\n## Gameplay Flow\n### What worked well\n- [Observation 1]\n\n### Pain points\n- [Issue 1 -- Severity: High/Medium/Low]\n\n### Confusion points\n- [Where the player was confused and why]\n\n### Moments of delight\n- [What surprised or pleased the player]\n\n## Bugs Encountered\n| # | Description | Severity | Reproducible |\n|---|-------------|----------|-------------|\n\n## Feature-Specific Feedback\n### [Feature 1]\n- **Understood purpose?** [Yes/No]\n- **Found engaging?** [Yes/No]\n- **Suggestions**: [Tester suggestions]\n\n## Quantitative Data (if available)\n- **Deaths**: [Count and locations]\n- **Time per area**: [Breakdown]\n- **Items used**: [What and when]\n- **Features discovered vs missed**: [List]\n\n## Overall Assessment\n- **Would play again?** [Yes/No/Maybe]\n- **Difficulty**: [Too Easy / Just Right / Too Hard]\n- **Pacing**: [Too Slow / Good / Too Fast]\n- **Session length preference**: [Shorter / Good / Longer]\n\n## Top 3 Priorities from this session\n1. [Most important finding]\n2. [Second priority]\n3. [Third priority]\n```\n\n---\n\n## Phase 2B: Analyze Mode\r\n\n---\n\r\n\nRead the raw notes at the provided path. Cross-reference with existing design documents. Fill in the template above with structured findings. Flag any playtest observations that conflict with design intent.\n\n---\n\n## Phase 3: Action Routing\n\nCategorize all findings into four buckets:\n\n- **Design changes needed** 鈥?fun issues, player confusion, broken mechanics, observations that conflict with the GDD's intended experience\n- **Balance adjustments** 鈥?numbers feel wrong, difficulty too spiked or too flat\n- **Bug reports** 鈥?clear implementation defects that are reproducible\n- **Polish items** 鈥?not blocking progress, but friction or feel issues for later\n\nPresent the categorized list, then route:\n\n- **Design changes:** \"Run `/propagate-design-change [path]` on the affected design document to find downstream impacts before making changes.\"\n- **Balance adjustments:** \"Run `/balance-check [system]` to verify the full balance picture before tuning values.\"\n- **Bugs:** \"Use `/bug-report` to formally track these.\"\n- **Polish items:** \"Add to the polish backlog in `production/` when the team reaches that phase.\"\n\n---\n\n## Phase 3b: Creative Director Player Experience Review\n\r\n","exit_code":0,"status":"completed"}}
{"type":"item.completed","item":{"id":"item_25","type":"command_execution","command":"\"C:\\\\Windows\\\\System32\\\\WindowsPowerShell\\\\v1.0\\\\powershell.exe\" -Command '$p='\"'C:\\\\Users\\\\GJM258\\\\.codex\\\\plugins\\\\cache\\\\game-design-skill\\\\game-design-skill\\\\0.2.0\\\\skills\\\\game-design-skill\\\\references\\\\upstream-workflow-prototype.md'; \"'$c=Get-Content $p; $c[70..90] -join \"`n\"; \"`n---`n\"; $c[239..251] -join \"`n\"'","aggregated_output":"worth considering if the timing is right.\n\nRead the concept description from the argument. Before building anything, define\nthe **falsifiable hypothesis** this prototype must answer:\n\n> *\"If the player [does X], they will feel [Y] 鈥?we will know this is true if [measurable signal Z].\"*\n\nGood: \"If the player swings on grapple hooks, traversal will feel fluid 鈥?we'll know if\nplayers chain 3+ swings without stopping within 2 minutes of picking it up.\"\n\nBad: \"Does this feel fun?\" 鈫?not testable, not falsifiable.\n\n**If the concept is too vague to form a hypothesis, stop here.** Ask the user to\nnarrow the question before proceeding. A prototype without a clear question wastes time.\n\nAlso ask: **\"What is the riskiest assumption in this concept?\"** That is the first\nthing the prototype should test 鈥?not the easiest part, the riskiest.\n\n---\n\n## Phase 2: Load Concept Context\r\n\n---\n\r\n\nDefine in 3鈥? bullet points the minimum viable prototype:\n\n- What is the falsifiable hypothesis?\n- What is the riskiest assumption 鈥?and how does this prototype test it first?\n- What is the absolute minimum needed to answer the question?\n- What is explicitly cut? (menus, save systems, error handling, polish, architecture 鈥?all of it)\n\n**Scope constraint:** A concept prototype tests ONE mechanic 鈥?not the whole game.\nIf scope covers more than one mechanic, cut it down. When in doubt, cut more.\n\nPresent this plan to the user before building. Get confirmation before proceeding.\n\r\n","exit_code":0,"status":"completed"}}
{"type":"item.completed","item":{"id":"item_27","type":"agent_message","text":"Review plan:\n1. Classify the overall product and the generative-card feature independently, using the skill’s removal tests.\n2. Separate project facts from source-backed methods, proposals, and unknowns.\n3. Judge whether the stated experience target is testable, then assess the interface, runtime authority chain, bounded freedom, legibility, Curator continuity, recovery, safety, privacy, retention, and evidence.\n4. End with the smallest next prototype, the playtest matrix it must cover, and a verdict among proceed, narrow, pivot, or stop."}}
{"type":"item.completed","item":{"id":"item_28","type":"agent_message","text":"**Verdict**\n\n`Narrow.` As described, this is an `AI-enhanced` deckbuilder with one potentially `AI-native` mechanic, not a fully AI-native product. The next step should be a much smaller prototype, because the current concept has four blockers: the experience target is not testable, the model-to-rules authority chain is undefined, the Curator memory promise has no continuity contract, and the evidence set avoids the real failure cases.\n\n**Project Facts**\n- The shipped loop still functions when runtime generation is unavailable: authored cards and previously generated cards remain playable.\n- The generative-card feature accepts fragments or up to 120 characters, then a model returns card fields and may invent a new rule.\n- The player sees only a spinner and a final card; there is no interpretation preview, no numeric/rule envelope, and no repair path except spending another token.\n- The Curator promises months-long memory and unrestricted typed conversation, while the plan stores complete conversations indefinitely.\n- Observed generation latency is 3 to 20 seconds, with no defined timeout, retry, fallback, authority owner, or behavior versioning.\n- External play evidence used curated successful cards; it did not test live ambiguous, unsafe, adversarial, outage, accessibility-alternative, or continuity cases.\n\n**Source-Backed Methods**\n- `AI role and removal tests:` removing runtime AI does not collapse the core roguelite deckbuilder, so the product class is `AI-enhanced`. Removing the generative-card feature does remove the custom card-creation value, so that feature is `AI-native` for now.\n- `Experience target:` “infinite possibility” is not a falsifiable play target. It names capability scope, not an observable player activity plus felt outcome.\n- `Player-AI interface:` the design over-promises expressive freedom, under-specifies anchors, hides interpretation, and conflicts with the “full gamepad support” promise because typing is effectively mandatory.\n- `Runtime loop and authority:` the concept skips inspectable intent extraction, deterministic validation, legal ranges, rule precedence, and final state authority. “The model may invent a new rule” is a design blocker unless there are explicit rules for creating rules.\n- `Bounded freedom and legibility:` the current loop encourages opaque rerolling rather than mastery. Players cannot learn what the system understood, why it rejected or transformed a request, or how to improve the next attempt.\n- `Curator continuity:` the promise is not testable yet because invariants, salience, contradiction handling, player correction, and memory-unavailable behavior are all undefined.\n- `Failure, safety, privacy, retention:` latency, outage, unsafe content, prompt-reveal attempts, and balance-breaking requests are core gameplay cases here, not post-fun polish. Indefinite raw conversation retention is a privacy risk, and the retention claims are hypotheses, not evidence.\n\n**Design Proposals**\n- Reframe the game as a deckbuilder with an experimental card-authorship feature, not as a whole-product AI-native claim.\n- Make the next prototype only about `bounded card authorship`: fragments plus tightly anchored text, schema-constrained outputs, visible interpretation, deterministic validation, one free repair path, and authored or pre-generated fallback. Cut runtime rule invention from this prototype.\n- Use a testable target such as: the player intentionally creates a card they can explain, accept, and use in the next fight as a real deckbuilding decision.\n- Defer the Curator to a second prototype: one stable voice, one remembered card, one correction path, one memory-loss fallback.\n- Prioritize playtests for expected inputs, ambiguous phrasing, unsupported requests, adversarial rule-breaking, repeated/paraphrased requests, timeout/outage behavior, gamepad-only play, and multi-session Curator recall.\n- If the bounded version is not compelling, pivot away from runtime generation rather than widening model freedom.\n\n**Unknowns**\n- Whether free-form text adds value beyond constrained fragment composition.\n- Whether card authorship or Curator continuity is the stronger return trigger.\n- Whether a short complete creative run is enough success without long-term retention.\n- What latency players will tolerate in the reward loop.\n- What consent, minimization, redaction, retention, access, and deletion policy is acceptable for Curator interactions.\n\n**Sources Applied**\n- `references/provenance.md`\n- `references/authoritative-sources.md`\n- `references/ai-native-game-design.md`\n- `references/upstream-workflow-prototype.md`\n- `references/upstream-workflow-playtest-report.md`"}}
